WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.200
Ah man, if you're like me, you remember this time during COVID-19 where we were locked

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:13.200
down.

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:14.200
It was terrible.

00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:16.080
I felt like I was trapped behind glass.

00:00:16.080 --> 00:00:17.080
I couldn't go outside.

00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:18.080
I hated it.

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:22.400
But of course, it's not as bad as some people had it during COVID.

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:24.760
They lost loved ones.

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:27.540
And of course, they could get sick themselves.

00:00:27.540 --> 00:00:32.820
So it's kind of strange that we're now back to this situation where we can, you know,

00:00:32.820 --> 00:00:33.820
have a conference.

00:00:33.820 --> 00:00:36.220
We can go out to bars and have fun.

00:00:36.220 --> 00:00:40.980
For a lot of people, it is very much like a pandemic never happened or will never happen

00:00:40.980 --> 00:00:44.540
again.

00:00:44.540 --> 00:00:49.380
For the people that think a pandemic will never happen again, I have some bad news.

00:00:49.380 --> 00:00:51.740
Pandemics are inevitable.

00:00:51.740 --> 00:00:57.020
And then some good news attached to that is that we can reduce the risk.

00:00:57.020 --> 00:01:02.299
So this is a quote from the leader of the Pandemic 2 project.

00:01:02.299 --> 00:01:10.820
She is responsible for increasing pandemic preparedness in the EU.

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:14.180
And what does reducing the risk mean in this case?

00:01:14.180 --> 00:01:18.260
Because I think it's kind of very important to understand what that means.

00:01:18.260 --> 00:01:24.820
It's that we can try to mitigate a pandemic when it comes.

00:01:24.820 --> 00:01:30.500
So it's very important to have really good data when you are confronted with a situation

00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:31.820
like that.

00:01:31.820 --> 00:01:36.059
But it might also mean, if we're very lucky, that we can actually completely smash a pandemic

00:01:36.059 --> 00:01:39.779
from ever happening, depending on our response.

00:01:39.779 --> 00:01:45.900
So this is a very, very far away from what I'm doing, but I'm sort of trying to work

00:01:45.900 --> 00:01:46.900
towards that goal.

00:01:46.900 --> 00:01:47.900
So who am I?

00:01:47.900 --> 00:01:54.379
I work at the RFEM, which is the Dutch Institute for Public Health and Environment of the Netherlands.

00:01:55.220 --> 00:01:59.459
Just to be sure, because I know there's a lot of Americans in here, I put a little map

00:01:59.459 --> 00:02:02.300
to show you where the Netherlands actually is.

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:05.099
It's this tiny little country in Europe.

00:02:05.099 --> 00:02:13.699
So I got hired by the RFEM two and a half years ago to work on the COVID-19 pipelines.

00:02:13.699 --> 00:02:19.419
So they were a completely new concept to the RFEM, because we had previously just did a

00:02:19.419 --> 00:02:25.059
lot of stuff manually, or sometimes in SAS scripts, but not very automated.

00:02:25.059 --> 00:02:34.139
So I got hired to help set this up and help run it.

00:02:34.139 --> 00:02:40.779
Now that COVID-19 has died down a lot, fortunately, we have switched our efforts to other diseases.

00:02:40.779 --> 00:02:45.039
And I'm going to talk today about influenza pipeline, so the common flu.

00:02:45.039 --> 00:02:46.039
And why the common flu?

00:02:46.279 --> 00:02:54.240
Because the flu has been actually one of the main sources of pandemics in recent history.

00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:58.759
So there is already a pipeline for this previously, it already existed.

00:02:58.759 --> 00:03:02.880
So very similar to toxo you had before, it was like a mess of data going in.

00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:09.440
You had to do a bunch of magic, and then a bunch of stuff goes out for different reasons.

00:03:09.440 --> 00:03:16.660
So it could be hospital data, data from GPs, nursing homes, municipalities, or statistics

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:17.660
from populations.

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:21.380
And we get handed a lot of different types of data.

00:03:21.380 --> 00:03:28.820
So it could be from a database, could be FTP, or, for example, just emails with CSV files.

00:03:28.820 --> 00:03:36.580
And what we did is we cleaned it up, and then we create reports for experts to analyze,

00:03:36.580 --> 00:03:40.639
and then make sure that it's not out of control.

00:03:40.639 --> 00:03:42.300
So this already exists.

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:45.179
So we already have a pipeline in place.

00:03:45.179 --> 00:03:48.179
So how bad can this existing pipeline be?

00:03:48.179 --> 00:03:55.100
So I have a tiny little demo here of an actual job that someone had to do every single week.

00:03:55.100 --> 00:03:58.919
So they never figured out how to put numbers above a bar chart.

00:03:58.919 --> 00:04:04.899
So the solution was to go to a graphical software, and then type in the numbers from an Excel

00:04:04.899 --> 00:04:05.899
sheet.

00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:09.179
So you can also make typos when you do this.

00:04:09.179 --> 00:04:11.899
So this is obviously very dangerous.

00:04:11.899 --> 00:04:14.979
And it's just because she inherited this job this way.

00:04:14.979 --> 00:04:19.739
This is just how she was taught to do it.

00:04:19.739 --> 00:04:21.899
So obviously, we need to automate this whole process.

00:04:21.899 --> 00:04:22.899
This is not OK.

00:04:22.899 --> 00:04:26.019
We learned a lot from COVID.

00:04:26.019 --> 00:04:28.019
It was a little bit messy and very chaotic during COVID.

00:04:28.019 --> 00:04:32.220
So now we have time to design our pipelines.

00:04:32.220 --> 00:04:35.459
So let's automate the whole thing.

00:04:36.019 --> 00:04:37.019
And I'm kind of a nerd.

00:04:37.019 --> 00:04:38.019
And I go to these conferences.

00:04:38.019 --> 00:04:40.100
And I get all these ideas.

00:04:40.100 --> 00:04:41.579
Some of these things are quite obvious.

00:04:41.579 --> 00:04:43.619
I have those data bricks.

00:04:43.619 --> 00:04:49.339
I also have fire on here, airflow for orchestration.

00:04:49.339 --> 00:04:52.500
So many ideas that I want to implement.

00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:56.700
But epidemiologists' reaction is more something like this.

00:04:56.700 --> 00:05:02.940
The reason for that is that the reason the epidemiologists are even involved in this

00:05:02.940 --> 00:05:06.179
is that they have to be really close to what they're doing to the data.

00:05:06.179 --> 00:05:11.579
So I will explain a little bit of reason for why that is a little bit later.

00:05:11.579 --> 00:05:17.540
But they have to be the ones that are running the pipeline, are actually constructing the

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:18.540
data themselves.

00:05:18.540 --> 00:05:21.779
That's sort of the way it's set up at RFM right now.

00:05:21.779 --> 00:05:23.540
So this doesn't work.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:28.299
So I proposed a couple of steps for a properly planned pipeline.

00:05:28.299 --> 00:05:29.700
And I will go through them one by one.

00:05:29.700 --> 00:05:34.940
So the first thing is we have to determine the requirements for a minimum viable product

00:05:34.940 --> 00:05:38.980
or a minimum viable pipeline, if you will.

00:05:38.980 --> 00:05:42.459
So to explain that, I will go back again to COVID-19, because that's where I have the

00:05:42.459 --> 00:05:44.579
most experience at RFM.

00:05:44.579 --> 00:05:49.940
And also because I was in a very similar situation to where the epidemiologists are right now

00:05:49.940 --> 00:05:52.420
at the RFM.

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:55.940
So two and a half years ago, when I started, there was one of the tasks that we were just

00:05:55.940 --> 00:05:56.940
handed.

00:05:56.940 --> 00:06:00.700
I had to sit behind a computer every day.

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:06.179
Someone of my team had to sit by the computer every day at 10 a.m. and press Control-Enter.

00:06:06.179 --> 00:06:12.019
We had to run one script and sit behind the computer and watch it go.

00:06:12.019 --> 00:06:16.820
The reason for that is that things were moving so fast, and we were constantly adding stuff

00:06:16.820 --> 00:06:18.459
to our code.

00:06:18.459 --> 00:06:21.640
And that was running into errors.

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:26.839
So what would happen is that if we would run it automatically, the job would fail,

00:06:26.839 --> 00:06:32.160
and we would have to then run the whole thing again and figure out where the bug was.

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:34.880
But the job was two hours long, and we needed the data in three hours.

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:40.440
So that was very challenging.

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:41.679
So what went wrong?

00:06:41.679 --> 00:06:47.279
So our error business was really low, because we were constantly changing the code.

00:06:47.279 --> 00:06:49.720
And because we were constantly changing the code, we had to do it manually, which means

00:06:49.799 --> 00:06:52.200
I was wasting a lot of time.

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:56.200
And our pipelines were not reproducible at all.

00:06:56.200 --> 00:07:01.000
And this is, of course, because we were changing them on the fly when we were editing.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:02.279
And I don't have logs.

00:07:02.279 --> 00:07:04.160
I don't have version control for it.

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:05.760
So that's kind of bad.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:10.799
So these were the main things that we had to challenge for our minimum viable pipeline.

00:07:10.799 --> 00:07:14.440
So some of these things are just agreements that we have to do with our team, so whoever

00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:15.600
is working on it.

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:21.179
So we decide we will not use GraphPad and then also image software, and we'll do everything

00:07:21.179 --> 00:07:24.320
in R. And we have to have a version control system.

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:26.880
And it's not just installing Git and running it once in a while.

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:30.519
No, we have to have agreements about how to actually use it.

00:07:30.519 --> 00:07:33.040
I will not focus on this too much today.

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:36.000
I will talk a bit more about the other part.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:39.799
It's very similar to the targets package, so that leaves you guys a nice question to

00:07:39.799 --> 00:07:42.959
ask on Slido.

00:07:42.959 --> 00:07:49.000
So I wanted to break down our pipeline into more modular chunks.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:53.279
So if you look at this little pseudocode that I have here, this is very similar to what

00:07:53.279 --> 00:07:59.119
our old pipeline would look like, the thing that I would have to run at 10 in the morning.

00:07:59.119 --> 00:08:02.440
We're importing a bunch of data.

00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:04.239
We're transforming the data.

00:08:04.239 --> 00:08:05.440
And then we're saving all of the data.

00:08:05.440 --> 00:08:08.440
And if something went wrong during this huge transformation step in the middle, then I

00:08:08.440 --> 00:08:13.640
would have to go in, fix it, and then rerun the step and the step below, et cetera.

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:19.279
So we propose to do it in a very similar manner to the targets package, to sort of separate

00:08:19.279 --> 00:08:20.279
this out.

00:08:20.279 --> 00:08:28.239
And this is also what was sort of talked about this morning at JD's talk, what was it again?

00:08:28.239 --> 00:08:34.039
Separate concerns and minimize complexity or separate concerns.

00:08:34.039 --> 00:08:41.760
So here we are, by creating modular chunks and breaking the problem down, we are separating

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:46.599
concerns so each step is smaller and easier to tackle.

00:08:46.599 --> 00:08:52.760
And basically, I'm also saying I'm equally genius as JD, so I'm just hanging up.

00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:59.119
So what we do here is we have our definition file where we say each step here, script one,

00:08:59.119 --> 00:09:02.159
script two, has an input and an output.

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:07.719
And then we have some way of running this as a pipeline, very similar to the TAR make.

00:09:07.719 --> 00:09:10.200
So here, there's our definitions again.

00:09:10.200 --> 00:09:16.760
And this would look into this, again, directed acyclic graph, this is what would get run.

00:09:16.760 --> 00:09:20.559
So that is sort of now our minimum viable pipeline.

00:09:20.559 --> 00:09:24.840
And the next step is to design a framework around that that would scale across organization.

00:09:24.840 --> 00:09:29.919
So this is what I was talking about earlier, that the epidemiologist actually needs to

00:09:29.919 --> 00:09:31.440
be involved there.

00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:36.919
The reason for that is that we're not just doing influenza, we have a lot of disease

00:09:36.919 --> 00:09:38.000
that we have to monitor.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:43.520
And each of them has their own unique quirks, unique data sources.

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:47.640
And it's really the epidemiologist's task to be really close to the data source and

00:09:47.640 --> 00:09:49.719
really contact them.

00:09:49.719 --> 00:09:56.520
And there's a lot of just emailing back and forth that us data scientists can do.

00:09:56.520 --> 00:10:00.719
So we rely on the epidemiologist to know what's happening.

00:10:00.719 --> 00:10:03.520
And our job is just to make their life easier.

00:10:03.520 --> 00:10:08.799
So we have to create this framework where they can focus just on the most important

00:10:08.799 --> 00:10:09.799
steps.

00:10:09.799 --> 00:10:14.400
So they have to understand what do I need to create, and we help them create this, break

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:17.219
it down into smaller steps and create this graph.

00:10:17.219 --> 00:10:21.960
And so they can focus on what script one does, what script two does, in this example.

00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:26.960
And what we do is we try to abstract away all of the stuff around it.

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:30.719
So these are the most important things that I was talking about earlier that was missing

00:10:30.719 --> 00:10:36.419
during the COVID-19 scripts, is that we didn't have logging.

00:10:36.419 --> 00:10:39.760
So we just add that as a layer in there.

00:10:39.760 --> 00:10:43.840
And also, of course, we need to go from this definition file to this DAG in the first place.

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:45.280
So that's something we do.

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:48.140
And we help with the import and the export of the data files.

00:10:48.140 --> 00:10:54.719
So we try to make it in such a way where it should not matter what you have, what kind

00:10:54.719 --> 00:11:01.239
of data you put in, or how you put the data in, and how you export the data also for future.

00:11:01.239 --> 00:11:06.719
So the epidemiologists, besides making this DAG and separate scripts, we just have to

00:11:06.719 --> 00:11:11.200
run pipeline, which is tar make in targets package.

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:20.280
And we in the back end, we created a package for internal tooling, and we create the run

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:22.200
pipeline function.

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:31.320
So we restart the logs, we interpret all of the steps, and we loop through the DAG to

00:11:31.320 --> 00:11:35.960
import the data, execute the script, export the data.

00:11:35.960 --> 00:11:43.239
So now, next to the third step, that's to allow space for extensions.

00:11:43.239 --> 00:11:46.559
This is the pipeline, as I showed you before.

00:11:46.559 --> 00:11:54.400
And what we wanted to do is to have the possibility to have very specific, to allow for specific

00:11:54.400 --> 00:11:57.359
extensions that are really important to us.

00:11:57.359 --> 00:12:02.280
So for example, you can imagine that they want to visualize this DAG, which is a relatively

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:05.119
simple thing to do, so that you can see what they're doing.

00:12:05.119 --> 00:12:10.719
You want to add static code checks as an option, so that we're making sure that they are doing

00:12:10.719 --> 00:12:12.919
what they say they're doing.

00:12:12.919 --> 00:12:14.960
And a very important one is to add metadata.

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:19.960
So when you are running a script, we can have metadata be collected and be published

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:27.520
in an internal RFVM-wide database, or for example, for scheduling.

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:32.719
So the idea behind it is that the epidemiologist doesn't have to change their code.

00:12:32.719 --> 00:12:38.000
They just have to update our internal package, and then the run pipeline transforms and adds

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:39.000
these extra things.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:44.000
So the static code check would be something like check steps.

00:12:44.039 --> 00:12:48.559
The metadata would just be one part of the loop, and they could have a separate visualization

00:12:48.559 --> 00:12:49.559
function.

00:12:49.559 --> 00:12:53.760
And of course, there's many ideas that are floating around that we want to do.

00:12:53.760 --> 00:12:54.760
So what is the current status?

00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:58.919
We now actually, we're finished with fully automating the flu surveillance, at least

00:12:58.919 --> 00:13:02.640
in the form of the minimum viable pipeline.

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:05.440
And we have now started with 20 new pipelines.

00:13:05.440 --> 00:13:08.000
So there's actually quite a lot of stuff happening in parallel.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.719
So a lot of epidemiologists working at the same time, and we are developing our package

00:13:11.719 --> 00:13:12.719
also at the same time.

00:13:13.239 --> 00:13:15.520
So we're quite busy.

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:19.820
So the first big extension to the package would be metadata.

00:13:19.820 --> 00:13:27.239
So we're working now on defining what is metadata in our case, and how are we storing that and

00:13:27.239 --> 00:13:29.760
sharing it across the RFVM.

00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:35.559
So to summarize my talk, using collaboration and clever design, we created a scalable framework

00:13:35.559 --> 00:13:39.919
for disease surveillance that gets us one step closer to preventing future pandemics.

00:13:40.239 --> 00:13:43.080
I mean, preventing is, okay, I hope so.

00:13:43.080 --> 00:13:49.359
But this is a long summary, and I like the seven Ps of the military, so I summarize it

00:13:49.359 --> 00:13:51.359
even further.

00:13:51.359 --> 00:13:56.159
Planned pathogen processing pipelines power pandemic preparedness.

00:13:56.159 --> 00:13:58.960
So it's much easier to remember, right?

00:13:58.960 --> 00:14:00.799
Okay, so thank you for your time.

00:14:01.039 --> 00:14:10.799
Thank you so much, appreciate it.

00:14:10.799 --> 00:14:16.960
So the other projects that you have right now, we create the other pipelines, are they

00:14:16.960 --> 00:14:22.799
still about surveillance, or is it something else that you're trying to track?

00:14:22.799 --> 00:14:27.440
So right now, we're mostly focused on getting surveillance out there.

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:31.599
Maybe I failed to mention it a little bit, but we want to have it as standardized as

00:14:31.599 --> 00:14:36.159
possible so that data scientists can still help epidemiologists, because if they start

00:14:36.159 --> 00:14:39.400
creating their own thing, then it's really hard to support them.

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:42.559
So it has to be as standardized as possible.

00:14:42.559 --> 00:14:47.760
So we're focusing now on getting surveillance pipelines up and running, but we also have

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:54.880
things like modeling happening that we might extend our functionality to in the future.

00:14:55.200 --> 00:15:00.400
But yeah, so there's also research happening, and we're probably not going to support that

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:05.760
much because that's going to be unique every time, and we'll not have a lot of repeating

00:15:05.760 --> 00:15:07.119
pipeline stuff happening.

00:15:07.119 --> 00:15:13.200
So we're mostly focusing on surveillance first, yeah.

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:18.359
And also the use of the YAML file, what was the reasoning behind using that particular

00:15:18.359 --> 00:15:21.599
method?

00:15:21.599 --> 00:15:27.679
So yeah, the Targets package uses R code.

00:15:27.679 --> 00:15:34.840
I find YAML to be more readable, and I looked at a couple, because Targets is the only one

00:15:34.840 --> 00:15:40.960
that's really mature for R, I think, but other programming languages have a similar thing.

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:47.840
And I find it really much more readable if it's in YAML, it's just me.

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:52.400
For example, the Kedro package, I think, also uses this Python thing, also uses YAML.

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:56.159
So it's more about readability to me.

00:15:56.159 --> 00:15:58.159
Yeah, I agree.

00:15:58.159 --> 00:16:01.440
Well, thank you again, I appreciate it.

00:16:01.440 --> 00:16:05.960
If you join me again to thank you, Patrick, thank you so much.

